answers.body_markdown:
I believe that you have 3 ways. 2 options if the MUL should be unique and another if uniqueness isn&#39;t required.

e.g. :-

    /* Unique constraint and therefore an auto-created index */
    CREATE TABLE messages1 (
    	id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT NOT NULL, 
    	group_id INTEGER, feat TEXT, 
    	UNIQUE(group_id, feat)
    );
    
    /* Unique constraint not required and therefore just an index */
    CREATE TABLE messages2 (
    	id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT NOT NULL, 
    	group_id INTEGER, feat TEXT 
    );
    CREATE INDEX messages_idx01 ON messages2 (group_id,feat);
    
    /* A specifically named UNIQUE index */
    CREATE TABLE messages3 (
    	id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT NOT NULL, 
    	group_id INTEGER, feat TEXT 
    );
    CREATE UNIQUE INDEX messages_idx02 ON messages3 (group_id,feat);

- Note the derived column types have been used.

  - That is column types (type affinity) are quite different in SQLite, they are more flexible and only an indication of the type of data stored. see [Datatypes In SQLite Version 3](https://www.sqlite.org/datatype3.html) 

 - e.g. BIGINT(16) has a derived column type of INTEGER, so INTEGER has been used.
 - Also note that AUTOINCREMENT has been used, however you should read [SQLite Autoincrement](https://sqlite.org/autoinc.html), as it would very likely not be required and that it introduces inefficiencies/overheads.

